CONSTRUCTION MANAGEMENT AGREEMENT
PREAMBLE
This CONSTRUCTION MANAGEMENT AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”), dated as of December 9, 2019 (the “Effective Date”), is made by and between AMERICAN TRANSMISSION COMPANY LLC, a Wisconsin limited liability company (“ATC”) and DAIRYLAND POWER COOPERATIVE, a cooperative association incorporated under the laws of the State of Wisconsin (“Dairyland”). ATC, and Dairyland may be collectively referred to in this Agreement as the “Parties” and individually referred to as a “Party.” RECITALS WHEREAS, ATC, ITC Midwest, LLC a Michigan limited liability company (“ITC Midwest”) and Dairyland entered into that certain September 2, 2016 Amended and Restated Joint Development Agreement (the “Joint Development Agreement” or “JDA”) with respect to development of the 345 kV electric transmission line and related facilities comprising the Cardinal-Hickory Creek segment of Multi-Value Project No. 5 (the “Project”); and WHEREAS, the JDA contemplates certain Definitive Agreements, including bi-lateral project ownership agreements, with one such agreement between ITC Midwest and Dairyland to address ITC Midwest’s and Dairyland’s undivided ownership as tenants in common of certain personal and real property interests making up part of the ITC Midwest Portion, and the other between ATC and Dairyland to address ATC’s and Dairyland’s undivided ownership as tenants in common of certain personal and real property interests making up part of the ATC Portion; and WHEREAS, the Parties have determined that this Agreement shall be one of the Definitive Agreements; and WHEREAS, the JDA provides for Dairyland to contribute nine percent (9%) of the Aggregate Investment in the Project, a portion of which will take the form of cash contributions to the costs of constructing the ATC Portion of the Line and the ITC Portion of the Line; and WHEREAS, in exchange for its Investment, Dairyland will obtain rights to the electric capacity of the Project and ownership as a tenant in common in real and personal property constituting the ATC Portion of the Line and the ITC Portion of the Line; and WHEREAS, Dairyland and ATC agree that ATC, as the anticipated tenant in common owner of approximately 91% in the real and personal property constituting the ATC Portion of the Line, will construct, operate and maintain the ATC Portion of the Line in accordance with Good Utility Practice, Applicable Law, and ATC’s Customary Business Practices; and WHEREAS, this Agreement is intended by the Parties to comprehensively define and address the Parties’ rights and obligations in relation to ATC’s construction of the ATC Portion of the Line.
NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the promises and the covenants and agreements set forth in this Agreement and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows: AGREEMENT Article 1 Definitions; Recitals Section 1.1 Definitions and Interpretation. This Agreement shall be interpreted in accordance with, and capitalized terms used in this Agreement shall have the meanings set forth in, Schedule 1.1. Section 1.2 Recitals. The foregoing recitals are incorporated into this Agreement as if fully set forth. Article 2 Relationship of Parties Section 2.1 Legal Relationship. The legal relationship of the Parties hereunder and in relation to the Project as a whole will be governed solely by the terms of the JDA, the Owners’ Coordination Agreement, this Agreement and any other Definitive Agreements to which both ATC and Dairyland are parties, and shall be limited further as follows: 2.1.1 The covenants, obligations and liabilities of the Parties set forth herein are intended to be several and not joint or collective and nothing herein contained will ever be construed to create an association, joint venture, trust, partnership or other legal entity or Person, or to impose a trust or partnership covenant, obligation, or liability on or with regard to either Party. 2.1.2 Neither Party will hold itself out to any Person as a partner of, or principal trustee or agent for, the other Party, except to the extent expressly authorized in this Agreement. No member or customer of a Party will be deemed a Party under this Agreement unless each of the Parties hereto have agreed in writing, and such member or customer has explicitly agreed in writing to be bound by all of the terms and conditions of this Agreement. 2.1.3 Each Party will be individually responsible for its own covenants, obligations, and liabilities as herein provided. No Party will be under the control of or will be deemed to control any other Party. No Party acting in any capacity will be the agent of or have a right or power to bind any other Party without its express written consent, except as set forth in this Agreement. 2.1.4 Except as may be expressly provided otherwise herein, the debts, obligations and liabilities of each Party pursuant to this Agreement or otherwise in connection with the Project, whether arising in contract, tort or otherwise, will be solely the debts, obligations and liabilities of such Party. 2.1.5 Neither Party nor any of its Affiliates shall owe a fiduciary duty or duty of loyalty to any other Party or any of the other Parties’ respective Affiliates in connection with this Agreement, the Project or the exercise, granting or withholding of its voting, consent or approval rights under this Agreement. To the maximum extent permitted by Applicable Law, each Party hereby releases and forever discharges any other Party and their respective Representative(s) from all liabilities based on a breach or violation of any fiduciary duty or duty of loyalty under this Agreement. Section 2.2 Relationship of JDA to this Agreement. Except as may be expressly provided to the contrary in this Agreement, the provisions of the JDA shall continue in effect after the Effective Date, provided, however, that: (i) where provisions of this Agreement are in conflict with those of the JDA, the provisions of this Agreement shall control, and (ii) where the provisions of this Agreement are consistent with those in the JDA but provide more specificity than provided in the JDA, the more specific provisions of this Agreement shall control. The Parties agree that the JDA shall terminate according to the terms of the JDA, unless sooner terminated by a writing by the all of the Parties to the JDA. Nothing in this Section 2.2 providing for termination of the JDA is intended to modify Section 8.2 (Survival) of the JDA. Section 2.3 Risk of Loss. Each Party will maintain the risk of loss of its property. Section 2.4 Statutory and Regulatory Obligations. The Parties acknowledge that compliance with the terms of this Agreement requires compliance with relevant obligations under Applicable Law. In particular, the Parties acknowledge that before effect may be given to this Agreement, it will be necessary for one or more of the Parties to obtain approval from one or more Governmental Authorities under various requirements of Applicable Law. Article 3 Term Section 3.1 Term. The term of this Agreement will commence on the Effective Date and will continue until this Agreement has been terminated pursuant to Article 15. Article 4 Reserved Article 5 Party Responsibilities Section 5.1 ATC Construction Management. 5.1.1 ATC shall perform or cause to be performed all work and services necessary to design, engineer, procure, construct, relocate as necessary, commission and place into service the Co-Owned Facilities, ATC Substation Assets, ATC Underbuild, relocation of Existing Transmission Lines and Existing Distribution Lines and all other Project-related construction work relating to the ATC Portion of the Line (collectively, the “Construction Work”), including the following, all in compliance with Applicable Law: (a) Provide overall coordination and administration of the Construction Work; (b) Manage and coordinate contractors engaged in providing any of the services associated with the Construction Work. (c) Manage and coordinate the Construction Work and the associated schedule; (d) In consultation with Dairyland, develop, revise and approve budgets, including the budget for the Construction Work (the “Construction Budget”); (e) Procure equipment, materials, construction aids and consumables for the Construction Work; (f) Prepare, as determined necessary by ATC, requests for information, requests for qualification and requests for proposals from Contractors, receive bids and prepare bid analyses; (g) Select Contractors and award Construction Agreements providing for the performance of Construction Work, including negotiation, execution and delivery of Construction Agreements and amendments and change orders thereto; (h) Administer Construction Agreements, including providing direction, as appropriate, to Contractors. (i) Keep, coordinate and organize records associated with the Construction Work in accordance with Section 8.2.1; (j) As required by Section 8.2.3, report to Dairyland on a periodic basis with respect to the Construction Work as set forth in this Agreement. (k) Coordinate with Contractors upon any suspension of performance of Construction Work or upon termination of this Agreement, including windup coordination and assistance; (l) Coordinate the transition from construction of the Co-Owned Facilities to operation and maintenance of the Co-Owned Facilities. (m) Manage surplus procured materials; (n) Oversee Commissioning of the Co-Owned Facilities, the ATC Substation Assets and the ATC Underbuild; and (o) Perform such other construction management tasks as necessary and consistent with ATC’s Customary Business Practices and Good Utility Practice with the goal of completing construction of the Co-Owned Facilities, the ATC Substation Assets and the ATC Underbuild by the Target In-Service Date. Section 5.2 ATC Management of Co-Owned Real Property. 5.2.1 ATC, for itself and on behalf of Dairyland, shall undertake all activities necessary to acquire and manage the acquisition and management of Co-Owned Real Property and the associated Land Contracts (“Real Property Management Services”), including the following, all in compliance with Applicable Law: (a) Acquisition of all Co-Owned Real Property necessary to: (a) complete construction of the Co-Owned Facilities and, (b) operate the Co-Owned Facilities, and (c) provide access for maintenance and improvement of the Co-Owned Facilities; (b) Site identification and identification of landowners and required crossing permits; communication with such landowners and their representatives to obtain required permissions; conduct due diligence; arrange for all necessary surveys; draft and negotiate the Land Contracts and close the acquisition of the Co-Owned Real Property and make all monetary payments associated therewith. (c) Administer and oversee all Construction Agreements entered into in connection with the acquisition of Co-Owned Real Property; (d) Initiate (through legal counsel retained by ATC) and manage and administer all Proceedings relating to condemnation of Co-Owned Real Property (including obtaining evidence and testimony regarding valuation, prior negotiations and other matters related to the condemnation); (e) Exercise commercially reasonable efforts to enforce the rights of ATC and Dairyland under the Land Contracts, including coordination of litigation and settlement of disputes arising out of such agreements; (f) Keep Dairyland reasonably apprised of significant issues and events which have occurred or are anticipated to occur in connection with the acquisition of Co-Owned Real Property; (g) Request, on reasonable notice, that Dairyland provide documents, instruments or take other actions reasonably necessary for ATC to timely provide the Real Property Management Services; (h) Keep, coordinate, organize, and make accessible to Dairyland the records associated with the acquisition of Co-Owned Real Property, including documenting all Co-Owned Real Property by files and maps, in accordance with formats that ATC employs in the normal course of its business; (i) Assist at the request of Dairyland (at Dairyland’s sole expense) with filings and/or recordings required by Dairyland’s Financing Party. 5.2.2 The Construction Work and the Real Property Management Services are known collectively as “the Services.” Section 5.3 Agency Authority of ATC. Dairyland designates and appoints ATC as its designated and disclosed agent to carry out, on behalf of Dairyland, the Services, and ATC accepts such appointment and agrees to execute such authority and to act on behalf of Dairyland, including with respect to all of the following: (a) Execution and filing and prosecution of all applications (and amendments and supplements thereto), certifications and instruments for, and submittal of all associated documentation required to obtain, Governmental Approvals from all Governmental Bodies needed for the Construction Work; and (b) Execution, delivery and recordation of all contracts, documents and instruments necessary or (as determined by ATC) desirable in order to perform or cause to be performed all Real Property Management Services, including the execution and delivery (to the extent permitted by Applicable Law) of the Land Contracts. Section 5.4 Cooperation. To the extent ATC, acting pursuant to the agency authority granted in Section 5.3, requires the cooperation or assistance (including execution of documents) of Dairyland, Dairyland agrees to give its prompt and reasonable assistance to ATC, and will make reasonable efforts to do so within ten (10) Business Days of ATC’s request for such assistance. ATC agrees to provide commercially reasonable cooperation with Dairyland to address issues raised by RUS with respect to the financing of Dairyland’s contributions to Construction Costs.
Section 5.5 Performance of Construction Work. ATC may, at its discretion, selfperform any portion of the Construction Work, or cause any portion of the Construction Work to be performed through Contractors. Article 6 Contracting Responsibilities Section 6.1 Construction Agreements. ATC shall bid, negotiate, enter into, administer and enforce contracts for, and otherwise arrange for the resources necessary, including for obtaining permits as necessary in the name of ATC and Dairyland, to cause the performance and completion of the Services, consistent with Good Utility Practice and ATC’s Customary Business Practices. (each such agreement, or subcontract thereto of any tier, a “Construction Agreement”). ATC has sole authority to approve all Construction Agreements, and amendments and change orders thereto, provided, however, that prior to ATC issuing a purchase order under a Construction Agreement valued at or more than one million dollars ($1,000,000), ATC shall inform Dairyland of (i) the identity of the contractor; (ii) a general description of the scope of work; and (iii) the projected contract amount. For avoidance of doubt, ATC may at its discretion, but is not required by this or any other Definitive Agreement, to engage in a competitive bidding process for any aspect of the Services, or Equipment or materials. Section 6.2 Construction Agreement Requirements. All Construction Agreements shall contain protections and covenants that are typically included in construction agreements for the protection and benefit of the project owner, including indemnities, limitations of liability, insurance, assignability and warranties. Section 6.3 Contract Administration. ATC shall administer and enforce all Construction Agreements as well as any other Co-Owned Facilities-related agreements entered into during the term of the JDA prior to the Effective Date, and shall do so in accordance with its Customary Business Practices, including with respect to all warranties obtained from Persons under such agreements. After the In-Service Date, ATC shall assume primary responsibility for the enforcement of all warranties in accordance with the requirements of the Parties’ Operation and Maintenance Agreement to be executed by the Parties after the Effective Date. Dairyland shall not communicate directly with any Contractor, but shall only do so indirectly through ATC. Article 7 Pre-Construction Activities. Section 7.1 Design of Co-Owned Facilities. ATC shall be solely responsible for completing the design of the Co-Owned Facilities. ATC may revise the Co-Owned Facilities’ design from time to time as necessary to satisfy the needs of the Project and in accordance with its Customary Business Practices and Good Utility Practice. Section 7.2 Project Execution. ATC shall perform the Construction Work in accordance with Schedule 5.1 of the Owners’ Coordination Agreement (Project Milestone Schedule). Section 7.3 Co-Owned Real Property Acquisition Plan. ATC shall develop a plan for acquisition of Co-Owned Real Property in accordance with ATC’s Customary Business Practices and Good Utility Practice. All Land Contracts will be executed and delivered by ATC on its and Dairyland’s behalf, and all Co-Owned Real Property shall be acquired in the name of both ATC and Dairyland as tenants-in-common. Article 8 Costs and Reporting Section 8.1 Construction Costs. 8.1.1 Construction Costs. The cost of the Services shall include costs for the following (individually, a “Construction Cost” and collectively, the “Construction Costs”): (a) All Project-related costs identified in the JDA as reimbursable to one or both Parties; (b) All amounts incurred for the Services; (c) Costs associated with Co-Owned Real Property, including acquisition of Co-Owned Real Property; preparation, negotiation, and execution and delivery of the Land Contracts; and the Real Property Management Services; (d) Amounts due to Contractors, consultants, and other Persons performing Services in accordance with this Agreement or the Construction Agreements (including costs for the acquisition of procured materials); (e) All costs relating to the discharge and payment of any liability, loss, Damage, or expense of defending, settling or otherwise administering Third Party Claims, except to the extent ATC is obligated to indemnify Dairyland; (f) Cost of insurance procured in the course of and in relation to the provision of the Services; (g) Initial payment and any annual payment incurred before the In-Service Date of the state of Wisconsin environmental impact fees, including any obligation to make one or more such payments that arises prior to the InService Date; (h) Sales Taxes and other Taxes arising from and payable to any Governmental Authority, payments in lieu of Taxes, and fees related to Governmental Approvals arising out of the performance of the Services or Construction Work under this Agreement, the Construction Agreements, Land Contracts or otherwise attributable to the performance of the Services, excluding income, gross receipts, license fees, franchise or Taxes similarly imposed or assessed on the results of operations of ATC, Dairyland, or a Contractor; (i) Costs incurred in connection with the cost of Proceedings relating to the CoOwned Facilities; (j) Any other costs incurred in connection with the performance of the Services, including (net of any reductions or adjustments received with respect thereto) rental charges, royalties and fees, field office costs, travel and relocation costs, professional services fees and costs incurred in connection with, or arising out of, performance bonds, security, utilities, safety, transport, storage and telecommunications; (k) All costs (less salvage credits, if any) associated with retirement of all or a portion of the Co-Owned Facilities, including dismantling, demolishing, and removing equipment and structures (including the cost of transportation and handling incidental thereto), security, disposing of debris, any site work necessary to effect retirement in accordance with Good Utility Practice, and the costs of any remediation, site restoration or monitoring; (l) All costs related to termination of the Project or this Agreement, including with respect to termination of Definitive Agreements, construction agreements, Land Contracts, and other contracts that relate to the CoOwned Facilities, in accordance with the terms thereof, and any cancellation costs, termination costs and Damages payable thereunder will constitute Construction Costs if (i) such costs and Damages would have constituted Construction Costs if the Project had not been terminated, or (ii) the respective Wind-up Plan is adopted prior to the Project Closeout, in which event all such costs and Damages will be paid by the Parties in accordance with their respective Ownership Percentage, and; (m) Any other costs that are otherwise agreed by the Parties to be Construction Costs, or which are Co-Owned Facilities-related costs that are to be capitalized under ATC’s or Dairyland’s formula rates. Section 8.2 Records and Reporting. 8.2.1 Records. Each Party shall maintain accurate documentation, records, books of account, invoices, contracts, mileage records and other evidence reasonably pertinent to the Construction Work and Construction Costs. All books, records and accounts required to be maintained pursuant to this Section 8.2.1 shall be maintained, as applicable: (i) in accordance with GAAP or, to the extent applicable, the Uniform System of Accounts prescribed by FERC for ATC and ITC Midwest, or the Uniform System of Accounts prescribed by RUS for Dairyland; and (ii) in a form satisfactory for the auditing requirements of an independent certified public accountant. All accounting records pertaining to the Project shall be maintained on the basis of a fiscal year that is the calendar year. Each Party shall, upon the reasonable request of any other Party given with reasonable prior notice, provide such other Party with access during normal business hours to all books, records and accounts related to any Construction Work, including any information reasonably necessary to permit such other Party to seek and obtain recovery of any costs related to the Project or to perform any of its obligations under this Agreement. 8.2.2 Inspection / Audit. Each Party shall have the right, at its sole cost, upon reasonable notice to any other Party, during such other Party’s regular business hours, and at such other Party’s corporate offices, to inspect, audit and make copies of any books, records, systems, policies and procedures, and other documentation and information related to the Services or Construction Costs that is in such other Party’s possession or under its control, including as-built drawings, maintenance logs and other documentation pertaining to the Services; provided, however, that this Section 8.2.2 shall not obligate any Party to create any information that does not already exist. A Party may exercise any rights described in Section 8.2.2 through an agent, employee or consultant designated in writing, including any accountant, engineer or attorney. 8.2.3 Progress and Financial Summary Report. On or before Monday of the fourth week of the first full month after the CPCN, the Franchise and all required federal agency Records of Decision have been issued, and prior to Monday of the fourth week of each month thereafter until the In-Service Date, ATC shall prepare and provide to Dairyland a progress and financial summary report. Each such report must include the following: (i) the amount of the current Construction Budget; (ii) a summary of actual Construction Costs incurred to date; (iii) a cash flow forecast, by month, of Construction Costs projected to be incurred through Project Closeout; (iv) the amount of and explanation for any funds received from Third Parties; progress since the previous month on the Construction Work and procurement of Land Contracts, and; (v) any material adverse events impacting the Services. 8.2.4 Project Closeout Report. Within ninety (90) days of Project Closeout, ATC shall prepare and provide to Dairyland a report which includes (i) a complete report of the Construction Costs, identifying costs invoiced and paid by Dairyland under Section 9.1 of this Agreement, together with such other amounts that are required to be paid on or before termination of this Agreement and (ii) a completed final unitization report prepared in accordance with Applicable Law, including in accordance with any and all FERC requirements. Article 9 Invoicing and Payment for Dairyland Share of Construction Costs Section 9.1 ATC Invoicing and Payment. Each month, beginning no later than the twentieth (20th) day of the month following the month in which ATC determines it has begun to incur costs in performance of its obligations under this Agreement. ATC shall invoice Dairyland for nine percent (9%) of the Construction Costs that ATC incurred in the previous month. ATC shall obtain lien waivers from Third Parties for Construction Work according to its Customary Business Practices. Section 9.2 Manner of Payment. All payments under this Agreement will be made by electronic funds transfer or wire transfer in immediately available funds for receipt by the due date. A Party may change its account for receiving a payment or delivery by giving written notice to the other Party at least five (5) Business Days prior to the scheduled date for the payment or delivery to which such change applies, provided, however, that no Party shall give effect to such change without first obtaining verbal confirmation from the other Party of the change. Section 9.3 No Counterclaim; No Set-Off. Subject to any good faith disputes regarding payment and addressed to the dispute resolution procedure set forth in Section 15.3 (the “Dispute Resolution Procedure”), each Party shall make payment of their share of Construction Costs to the other Party, as and when due, without demand, counterclaim, setoff, deduction or defense. Section 9.4 Delinquent Payments. Payments not made when due under this Agreement will bear interest from the due date thereof until the date paid at the Late Payment Rate. Section 9.5 Payment not Acceptance. Subject to the prohibition on withholding amounts set forth in Section 9.4, payment hereunder neither constitutes acceptance of the Services nor forecloses any right of audit or dispute with respect to such payments. Section 9.6 Amounts to be Credited. ATC shall credit to Dairyland any amount of Construction Costs that Dairyland paid to ATC but which have subsequently been refunded or otherwise lawfully recovered by ATC, including refunds of Taxes, refunds made by Contractors or payment of insurance proceeds relating to any ATC or Dairyland insurance claim, net of the costs associated with such recovery. Article 10 Completion of Co-Owned Facilities Section 10.1 Completion. ATC shall provide the Services in accordance with both Good Utility Practice and ATC’s Customary Business Practices, such that the Construction Work is complete, and the Co-Owned Facilities are ready to be placed in commercial service, by the InService Date. ATC shall promptly provide written notice to Dairyland of the dates on which the Co-Owned Facilities will be and have been energized and made available to MISO for transmission service. Article 11 No Warranty on Services or Construction Work Section 11.1 ATC MAKES NO WARRANTY OR GUARANTY TO DAIRYLAND OR ANY OTHER PERSON, EITHER EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, WITH RESPECT TO THE PROJECT, OR THE SERVICES AND ATC EXPRESSLY DISCLAIMS, AND DAIRYLAND EXPRESSLY WAIVES, ANY AND ALL WARRANTIES IMPLIED BY LAW, INCLUDING THE WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY AND FITNESS. Article 12 Parties’ Representations and Warranties Section 12.1 Representations and Warranties. Each Party, as of the Effective Date makes the following representations and warranties to the other Party, which representations and warranties survive the execution and delivery of this Agreement: 12.1.1 Organization and Good Standing. Such Party is, as set forth in the preamble to this Agreement, an agency, non-profit corporation, cooperative association, municipal corporation, political subdivision, limited liability company, corporation or a similar Person organized, existing and in good standing under the laws of the state of its formation and authorized to conduct business in each state in which authorization may be required to perform its obligations under this Agreement. 12.1.2 Power and Authority. Such Party has the power and authority to enter into and perform this Agreement and is not (i) prohibited from entering into this Agreement or (ii) , and shall not in the future be, prevented from, or otherwise become in breach of its governing documents when, discharging and performing any and all covenants and obligations on its part to be performed under and pursuant to this Agreement. 12.1.3 Authorization. Such Party has taken all action required by Applicable Law and its governing documents in order to approve, execute and deliver this Agreement. 12.1.4 No Violation. The execution and delivery of this Agreement by such Party, the performance by such Party of its obligations hereunder and the consummation by such Party of the transactions contemplated herein do not and will not: (i) contravene any Applicable Law in effect on the Effective Date or any Order in effect on the Effective Date of an arbitrator having jurisdiction over such Party or its property, (ii) result in a breach or violation of any of the terms and provisions of, or constitute a default under, any indenture, mortgage, deed of trust or other agreement in effect on the Effective Date and to which such Party is a party or by which it or its property is bound, or (iii) result in the creation or imposition of any Lien upon the Ownership Percentage or any other property of the other Party, other than Liens arising from the contractual rights of the Parties contained in this Agreement or any other Definitive Agreement. 12.1.5 Approvals and Consents. No approval, consent or authorization of any Governmental Authority or other Person is required for the execution and delivery by such Party of this Agreement, or any other Definitive Agreement or the performance by such Party of its obligations hereunder or thereunder, except such approvals, consents or authorizations that (i) have been given or obtained by such Party and are in full force and effect or (ii) are set forth in Schedule 12.1.5. 12.1.6 Binding Effect. This Agreement has been executed and delivered by such Party. Assuming that the other Party has the requisite power and authority, and has taken all necessary action to execute and deliver this Agreement, this Agreement is the legal, valid and binding obligation of such Party enforceable in accordance with its terms, except as limited by laws of general applicability limiting the enforcement of creditor’s rights (e.g., bankruptcy, insolvency, moratorium) or by the exercise of judicial discretion in accordance with general principles of equity. Article 13 Default and Limitation of Liability Section 13.1 Defaults Generally. Any failure of a Party to perform a material obligation under this Agreement shall constitute a default of this Agreement (each such failure, a “Default”). Section 13.2 Construction Cost Payment Defaults. Each failure of a Party to pay amounts invoiced under this Agreement within thirty (30) days after such payment was due shall constitute a separate Default under this Agreement. If such Default continues for thirty (30) days after written notice from the non-defaulting Party, the non-defaulting Party shall pay such amounts and the Ownership Percentages shall be recalculated to reflect such payments. Upon payment of such amounts by the non-defaulting Party, the defaulting Party shall have waived any opportunity or right to re-establish the Ownership Percentage that would have accrued in the absence of such default. Section 13.3 Remedies for Default. For Defaults other than Defaults under Section 13.2 for non-payment of Construction Costs, the non-defaulting Party will be entitled to recover from the defaulting Party for Damages incurred by such non-defaulting Party that arise from, in connection with or incident to the Default, and to any appropriate equitable remedy, including but not limited to specific performance. Section 13.4 No Consequential Damages. All payments will first be applied to the payment of accrued but unpaid interest. The amount of any judgment obtained by one Party against another in any Proceeding arising out of a Default by such other Party under this Agreement will bear interest until paid at the greater of (i) the Late Payment Rate, or (ii) the judgment rate under Applicable Law. Article 15 Termination, Force Majeure, and Dispute Resolution Section 15.1 Termination. This Agreement shall terminate upon the earlier of (i) termination of the Project Ownership Agreement; and, (ii) ninety (90) days after Project Closeout. Section 15.2 Force Majeure events. The Parties will be excused from performing their respective obligations other than payment obligations under this Agreement for the duration of a Force Majeure event, and will not be liable in damages or otherwise if and to the extent that they are unable to so perform or are prevented from performing by a Force Majeure event, provided that: (i) the non-performing Party, as promptly as practicable after the occurrence of the Force Majeure event, but in no event later than five (5) days thereafter, gives the other Party written notice describing the particulars of the occurrence; (ii) the suspension of performance is of no greater scope and of no longer duration than is reasonably required by the Force Majeure event; (iii) the non-performing Party uses good faith and commercially reasonable efforts to remedy its inability to perform; and (iv) as soon as the non-performing Party is able to resume performance of its obligations excused as a result of the occurrence, each Party will give prompt written notification thereof to the other Party. Under no circumstance will an event of Force Majeure excuse a Person’s obligations to make payments when due under this Agreement, unless such Force Majeure event results in a failure of the Federal Reserve wire system or other failure of the banking system that deprives a Person of access to otherwise available funds. Section 15.3 Dispute Resolution. Prior to a Party initiating any Proceeding to resolve a dispute between the Parties, the Party who wishes to pursue the remedy must provide the other Party a written dispute notice which describes in reasonable detail the nature of the dispute and specifies the resolution sought. The notice shall also provide the name, title and contact information of a senior executive of the initiating Party, and propose a time on a date between five (5) and ten (10) Business Days after issuance of the dispute notice for the Parties to conduct an initial meeting to discuss and attempt to resolve the dispute. Within five (5) Business Days following receipt of a dispute notice, the responding Party will appoint a senior executive assigned to participate in efforts to settle the dispute and will identify that senior executive to the initiating Party. Within ten (10) Business Days following receipt of a dispute notice, the senior executives will meet by phone or in person. The purpose of this initial meeting will be for the senior executives to attempt in good faith to reach a mutually acceptable resolution of the dispute. If there is no resolution of the dispute through the meeting of the senior executives, either Party is free to seek all rights and remedies available at law or in equity. Section 16.2 Confidentiality. 16.2.1 Treatment of Confidential Information. The Parties intend to exchange confidential information among the Parties relating specifically to this Agreement or the Project. “Confidential Information” as used in this Agreement means all information disclosed by a Party to the other Party or its officers, directors, employees, agents, consultants and advisors in connection with this Agreement or the Project including any business, technical, marketing, financial or other information, whether in electronic, oral or written form. Each Party agrees to use Confidential Information solely for the activities contemplated by this Agreement (each a “Permitted Purpose”). Each Party will keep Confidential Information confidential and will advise its Representatives not to disclose to any Person any Confidential Information other than for a Permitted Purpose; provided, however, that Confidential Information may be disclosed to a Party’s Representatives who may need to know such Confidential Information; provided, further, however, that such Representatives are informed by the Party the confidential nature of the Confidential Information and that they will be bound by the confidentiality provisions of Section 16.2 to the same extent as if they were parties hereto. Each Party agrees that it will be responsible for any breach of Section 16.2 by any of its Representatives and for any use of the Confidential Information by any of them for any purpose other than a Permitted Purpose. Written documents, electronic documents and other physical information will be deemed Confidential Information, and protected hereby, only if clearly and prominently marked and identified as “CONFIDENTIAL.” Oral or other non-written communications will be deemed Confidential Information only if they are declared to be Confidential Information at the time disclosed. 16.2.2 Exceptions. Notwithstanding Section 16.2.1, the term “Confidential Information” does not include any information that (i) is or becomes generally available to the public other than as a result of a disclosure by Party, or any of its respective Representatives in violation of Section 16.2.1; (ii) was within a Party’s possession before its being furnished to such Party by or on behalf of the other Party; (iii) becomes available to a Party on a non-confidential basis from a source other than the other Party or any of their respective Representatives, provided that such recipient does not know that such source is bound by a confidentiality agreement with, or other contractual, legal or fiduciary obligation of confidentiality to, any other Person with respect to such information; or (iv) is independently developed by a Party, without access to the Confidential Information. 16.2.3 Requirement to Disclose Confidential Information. If a Party (i) is required by legal process, a Governmental Body, Arbitrator or otherwise by operation of law to disclose any Confidential Information of the other Party (“Disclosing Party”), or (ii) determines that it is necessary to disclose any Confidential Information in connection with Proceedings before any Governmental Body with jurisdiction over a Party’s rates or operations, then to the extent legally permissible, the Party, as applicable, will give prompt prior notice of such impending disclosure to the Disclosing Party so that the Disclosing Party at its own cost may seek a protective Order or other appropriate remedy. The Disclosing Party (a) will disclose only that portion of the Confidential Information that it is legally required to disclose or determines that is necessary to disclose in connection with Proceedings before any Governmental Body with jurisdiction over a Party’s rates or operations, (b) will give prompt notice of same to the Disclosing Party, and (c) will reasonably cooperate with the Disclosing Party in connection with the efforts of the Disclosing Party seeking a protective Order or other appropriate remedy. 16.2.4 Compliance with FERC Standards of Conduct. Each Party will not, directly or indirectly, reveal any non-public transmission function information (as defined in 18 C.F.R. §§ 358.3j, as such rules may be interpreted, amended or replaced by FERC from time to time, and hereinafter referred to as “Transmission Information”) in a manner that violates 18 C.F.R. §§ 358.6 and 358.7, as such rules may be interpreted, amended or replaced by FERC from time to time (the “FERC Standards of Conduct”). To the extent applicable, a disclosure (inadvertent or otherwise) of Transmission Information by a Party must be appropriately addressed by such Party pursuant to 18 C.F.R. § 358.7 or any successor provision. 16.2.5 Restrictions on Access to Critical Energy Infrastructure Information. Each Party certifies for itself and its Representatives who may be granted access to “critical energy infrastructure information” (“CEII”) as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 388.113(c)(1) or any successor provision that (i) it and each of its Representatives are aware of the requirements of 18 C.F.R. Part 388 with regard to CEII, and (ii) it has no reason to believe that it or its Representatives would be restricted from access to CEII. To the extent applicable, a disclosure (inadvertent or otherwise) of CEII by a Party must be appropriately addressed by such Party pursuant to 18 C.F.R. § 358.7(a)(2) or any successor provision. 16.2.6 Breach of Confidentiality Provisions. Each Party expressly agrees that a breach of any of the terms or conditions of Section 16.2 would result in irreparable harm and that money would not be a sufficient remedy for any such breach. Accordingly, in the event of a breach or threatened breach by a Party or by any of its Representatives of any of the provisions of Section 16.2 (and in addition to any other remedy provided by law or in equity), each Party agrees that the Party which such breach would harm will be entitled to seek appropriate equitable relief, including injunctive relief and specific performance. 16.2.7 Termination of Confidentiality Restrictions. Subject to Applicable Law, including the FERC Standards of Conduct, the Parties shall be bound by the provisions of Section 16.2 for a period of three (3) years following the termination of this Agreement; provided, however, that the foregoing expiration shall not be applicable to (i) trade secrets under state law which are disclosed as Confidential Information, for which the covenants herein shall survive indefinitely, and (ii) CEII under the Code of Federal Regulations, and any successor provision, for which the covenants herein shall survive indefinitely. 16.2.8 Other Agreements. The obligations, rights and covenants set forth in Section 16.2 shall be supplemental to, and do not supersede, those contained in the Confidentiality Agreement and that certain January 24, 2014 Confidentiality and Joint Prosecution Agreement by and among the Parties and ITC Midwest. C. D. ATC will develop and independently construct, own, operate, and maintain the portion of the Project that is (i) the ATC Arpin substation (the “Arpin Substation”) expansion and the ATC owned portion of the Columbia substation (the “Columbia Substation”) expansion, and (ii) the rebuild and expansions of various ATC transmission lines including a new 345 kV transmission line from the “Golden Spike” on the Project map to the Arpin Substation and from the Arpin Substation to the Columbia Substation and from the Columbia Substation to near Wyoceana and, with respect to the foregoing, any upgrades to remote end substations owned by ATC (the “ATC Project”), as set forth in Exhibit A-2A (ATC Project Map (Northern Route Alternative)) and Exhibit A-2B (ATC Project Map (Southern Route Alternative)) (individually, each an “ATC Project Map” and, collectively, the “ATC Project Maps”).
